# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-hamilton
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] The **Annapolis Convention** (formally titled a **Meeting of Commissioners to Remedy Defects of the Federal Government**) was a national political convention held September 11–14, 1786 in the old Senate Chamber of the Maryland State House in Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] In it twelve delegates from five U.S. states (New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Delaware, and Virginia) gathered to discuss and develop a consensus on reversing the protectionist trade barriers that each state had erected.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] At the time, under the Articles of Confederation, each state was largely independent from the others, and the national government had no authority to regulate trade between and among the states.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and North Carolina had appointed commissioners, who failed to arrive in Annapolis in time to attend the meeting, and Connecticut, Maryland, South Carolina, and Georgia had taken no action at all.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] The convention also related to George Washington's plans concerning the waterways connecting the Potomac and the Ohio River.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] Most of the delegates to the meeting were tasked only to take up the issue of trade among the states, but New Jersey's delegates were authorized to discuss a broader scope of reforms.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] The group realized that the issue of trade touched upon many other aspects of the Confederation and that a future meeting with a broader scope would be necessary to adequately address the problems.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] The final report of the convention was adopted unanimously and sent to the Congress of the Confederation and to the states.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] The report sought support for a broader constitutional convention to be held the following May in Philadelphia.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] It expressed the hope that more states would be represented and that their delegates or deputies would be authorized to examine areas broader than trade alone.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] Because of the few representatives in attendance, their authority was limited.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] It is unclear how much weight the convention's call carried, but the urgency of the need for constitutional reform was highlighted by a number of rebellions that took place all over the country.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] Although most of them were easily suppressed, Shays' Rebellion lasted from August 1786 to February 1787.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] The rebellion called attention to both popular discontent and government weakness.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1786-annapolis-convention] The direct result of the Annapolis Convention's report and the ensuing events was the 1787 Philadelphia Convention, when the United States Constitution was drafted.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The **1791 United States Senate election in New York** was held on January 19, 1791, by the New York State Legislature to elect a U.S. senator (Class 1) to represent the State of New York in the United States Senate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The election was conducted by a system of approval voting.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Incumbent Senator Philip Schuyler was not re-elected.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Aaron Burr, Attorney General of New York, won majority support in both the State Senate and State Assembly to succeed him.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In July 1789, Philip Schuyler and Rufus King had been elected to the U.S.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Schuyler had drawn the short term which would expire on March 3, 1791.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] At the State election in April 1790, nominal Federalist majorities were elected to both houses of the 14th New York State Legislature, but many Federalists were friendly to the Democratic-Republican Governor George Clinton, party lines not being drawn very strictly.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Schuyler, the incumbent, and Benson were both Federalists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Burr was not affiliated with the Federalist Party but was considered a moderate member of the emergent Jeffersonian faction that would coalesce as the Democratic-Republican Party the next year.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Burr was declared elected after receiving a majority of "Yeas" in each chamber of the legislature.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Schuyler and Benson were both rejected by the Assembly and no vote was taken on either in the Senate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The incumbent Schuyler was defeated, despite the nominal majority of his party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Many of the Federalists took the opportunity to show their disapproval of both Schuyler's haughtiness and the financial policies of Alexander Hamilton, the U.S.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Secretary of the Treasury and Schuyler's son-in-law.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Besides, the Livingston faction of the Federalist Party felt betrayed after the election of Rufus King over their candidate James Duane in 1789, and now allied themselves with Clinton and later became Democratic-Republicans.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] After a one-day special session of the U.S.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Senate on March 4, 1791, the 2nd United States Congress convened for the regular session on October 24, 1791, at Congress Hall in Philadelphia.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On November 8, 1791, the State's Council of Appointments declared the office of attorney general vacant, and appointed Morgan Lewis to succeed Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1791-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The song "Schuyler Defeated" from the 2015 musical Hamilton focuses on Hamilton confronting Burr following the election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 3, 1800.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election in U.S. history to be a rematch, the first election where an incumbent president lost re-election, leading to the first time in modern history where a national government changed hands peaceably following a free election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Adams had narrowly defeated Jefferson in the 1796 election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Under the rules of the electoral system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] As Jefferson received the second-most votes in 1796, he was elected vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In 1800, unlike in 1796, both parties formally nominated tickets.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Jefferson and Aaron Burr, while the Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of Adams and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Each party formed a plan by which one of their respective electors would vote for a third candidate or abstain so that its preferred presidential candidate (Adams for the Federalists and Jefferson for the Democratic-Republicans) would win one more vote than the party's other nominee.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The chief political issues revolved around the fallout from the French Revolution and the Quasi-War.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Federalists favored a strong central government and close relations with Great Britain.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans favored decentralization to the state governments, and the party attacked the taxes the Federalists imposed.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans also denounced the Alien and Sedition Acts, which the Federalists had passed to make it harder for immigrants to become citizens and to restrict statements critical of the federal government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans were well organized at the state and local levels, while the Federalists were disorganized and suffered a bitter split between their two major leaders, Adams and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] According to historian John Ferling, the jockeying for electoral votes, regional divisions, and the propaganda smear campaigns created by both parties made the election recognizably modern.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] At the end of a long and bitter campaign, Jefferson and Burr each won 73 electoral votes, Adams won 65, and Pinckney won 64.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Federalists swept New England, the Democratic-Republicans dominated the South, and the parties split the Mid-Atlantic states of New York, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans' assumption that one or more electors in Rhode Island, Vermont, New Jersey, Georgia, Kentucky, or Tennessee would vote for Jefferson and not Burr resulted in a tie, known as the Burr dilemma.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] It necessitated a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Under the terms laid out in the Constitution, the outgoing House of Representatives chose between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Burr was accused of campaigning for the presidency himself in the contingent election despite being a member of Jefferson's party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Each state delegation cast one vote, and a victory in the contingent election required one candidate to win a majority of the state delegations.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots of the contingent election, as most Federalist representatives backed Burr and all Democratic-Republican representatives backed Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Hamilton favored Jefferson over Burr, and he convinced several Federalists to switch their support to Jefferson, giving Jefferson a victory on the 36th ballot.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Jefferson became the second consecutive incumbent vice president to be elected president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1824 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Both parties used congressional nominating caucuses to formally nominate tickets for the first time.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of incumbent President John Adams of Massachusetts and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Pinckney had fought in the American Revolutionary War and later served as the minister to France.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Vice President Thomas Jefferson of Virginia and former Senator Aaron Burr of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Jefferson had been the runner-up in the previous election and had co-founded the party with James Madison and others, while Burr was popular in the electorally important state of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] While the 1800 election was a re-match of the 1796 election, it ushered in a new type of American politics, a two-party republic and acrimonious campaigning behind the scenes and through the press.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] On top of this, the election pitted the "larger than life" Adams and Jefferson, who were formerly close allies turned political enemies.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The campaign was bitter and characterized by slander and personal attacks on both sides.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Federalists spread rumors that the Democratic-Republicans were radical atheists who would ruin the country (based on the Democratic-Republican support for the French Revolution).
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In 1798, George Washington had complained "that you could as soon scrub the blackamoor white, as to change the principles of a professed Democrat; and that he will leave nothing unattempted to overturn the Government of this Country".
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Meanwhile, the Democratic-Republicans accused Federalists of subverting republican principles with the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] They also accused Federalists of favoring Britain in its war with France in order to promote aristocratic, anti-democratic values.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Adams was attacked by both the opposition Democratic-Republicans and a group of so-called "High Federalists" aligned with Alexander Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] "High Federalists" considered Adams too moderate and would have preferred the leadership of Alexander Hamilton instead.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Hamilton had apparently grown impatient with Adams and wanted a new president who was more receptive to his goals.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] During Washington's presidency, Hamilton had been able to influence the federal response to the Whiskey Rebellion (which threatened the government's power to tax citizens).
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] When Washington announced that he would not seek a third term, the Federalists and Adams regarded himself as next-in-line.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Hamilton appears to have hoped in 1796 that his influence within an Adams administration would be as great as or greater than in Washington's.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] By 1800, Hamilton had come to realize that Adams was too independent and thought the Federalist vice presidential candidate, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, more suited to serving Hamilton's interests.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In his third sabotage attempt toward Adams, Hamilton quietly schemed to elect Pinckney to the presidency.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Given Pinckney's lack of political experience, he would have been expected to be open to Hamilton's influence.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] However, Hamilton's plan backfired and hurt the Federalist party, particularly after one of his letters, a scathing criticism of Adams that was fifty-four pages long, fell into the hands of a Democratic-Republican and soon after became public.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] It embarrassed Adams and damaged Hamilton's efforts on behalf of Pinckney, not to mention speeding Hamilton's own political decline.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The contemporarily unorthodox public campaigning methods employed in 1800 were first employed by Jefferson's running mate and campaign manager, Aaron Burr, who is credited by some historians with inventing the modern electioneering process.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Yet, throughout this entire process, the candidates themselves were conspicuously missing from the campaigning, at least publicly, due to fears that they may otherwise be tagged as "demagogues".
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Even a visit John Adams made to Washington was made into a public point of contention.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Partisans on both sides sought any advantage they could find.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In several states, this included changing the process of selecting electors to ensure the desired result.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In Georgia, Democratic-Republican legislators replaced the popular vote with selection by the state legislature.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In Virginia, the Democratic-Republican-controlled legislature switched from electoral districts to a general ticket, a winner-take-all system.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Federalist legislators also switched methods, switching from districts and general tickets to legislature votes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, respectively.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, the General Assembly was split, with the Democratic-Republican-dominated House wishing to retain the general ticket and the Federalist-controlled Senate wishing to return to the district system, hoping to win at least some electoral votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Eventually, this deadlock was broken by a last-minute compromise between the chambers that gave the Democratic-Republican eight electors and the Federalists seven.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In New York, the rejection to change the selection method backfired on the Federalists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In March 1800, two months before the assembly elections, the Democratic-Republicans attempted to pass a bill that would switch from a legislature vote to electoral districts, hoping they would secure at least a third of the state's seats.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Federalists defeated the measure, believing that they would win control of both chambers and award all of the state's electoral votes to the Federalist nominees.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] However, in the April state elections, Aaron Burr's effective mobilization of the vote in New York City led to a reversal of the Federalist majority in the state legislature, providing crucial support for the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In response to the Federalist defeat, Hamilton attempted to get Governor John Jay to call a special session of the outgoing Federalist-dominated New York legislature.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Hamilton's plan was for the outgoing assembly to pass legislation that would establish the popular election of electors through electoral districts, a strategy almost certain to secure nine or ten of the twelve elector slots for the Federalists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Jay refused to participate in such an underhanded scheme.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Federalist legislature in Connecticut did not change the method of voting but instead passed a "stand up" election law, mandating that all votes be cast publicly and orally, an intimidating procedure that ordinarily favored those in power.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] As election day neared, the election was too close to call.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The last state to vote, South Carolina, chose its electors on December 2, and would become key to determining the election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The state elections in mid-October had produced an assembly that was about evenly divided between committed Federalists and Republicans, with 16 unaffiliated representatives who were all strongly pro-Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Many of the elected Jeffersonians were also supporters of Pinckney, the revered native son of the state.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] If South Carolina's electors gave their votes to Jefferson and Pinckney, then Pinckney would place an electoral vote behind Jefferson, becoming the vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] However, Pinckney stayed loyal to the instructions of his party's caucus and was adamant that any elector who voted for him must also vote for Adams.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] With uncommitted legislators not willing to desert Jefferson and Pinckney unwilling to abandon Adams, the uncommitted legislators eventually reluctantly agreed to support Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Under the United States Constitution as it then stood, each elector cast two votes, and the candidate with a majority of the votes was elected president, with the vice presidency going to the runner-up.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Federalists therefore arranged for one of their Rhode Island electors to vote for John Jay instead of Charles Pinckney to prevent the election from resulting in a tie.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] A letter to Jefferson from Peter Freneau assured him that a member of the Republican delegation from South Carolina would vote for George Clinton instead of Aaron Burr and a report from Georgia indicated that two of its electors would deny Burr their votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] However, this information proved faulty.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Thus, all of the Democratic-Republican electors cast their votes for both Jefferson and Burr, 73 in all for each of them.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] According to a provision of the United States Constitution, a tie in a case of this type had to be resolved by the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In the outgoing House, the Federalists had a majority of 60 seats to 46.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] When the electoral ballots were opened and counted on February 11, 1801, the certificate of election from Georgia was different than the others.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Georgia had sent the original oral ballot.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In 2004, David Fontana and Bruce Ackerman asserted that Georgia's certificate did not take the constitutionally mandated form of a "List of all the Persons voted for, and of the Number of Votes for each".
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] They claimed that Vice President Jefferson, who was presiding over the counting of electoral votes in his role as President of the Senate, immediately counted the votes from Georgia as votes for Jefferson and Burr, though they observed that "no objections were raised".
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Pinckney, and John Jay) in the House of Representatives.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] With these votes, the total number of votes for Jefferson and Burr was 73, which gave them a majority of the total, but they were tied.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Holly Brewer, a legal historian, argued that the counting of the Georgia ballot did not support Ackerman and Fontana's theory.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Brewer's arguments helped to influence Vice President Pence's decision to reject the theory that he had such powers, via Judge J.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Jefferson and Burr carried every state that had supported the Democratic-Republicans in 1796, made gains in Maryland, and picked up Burr's home state of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In the six states choosing electors by some form of popular vote, they won a landslide over Adams and Pinckney, polling 15,846 more votes than the Federalist ticket.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Adams made gains in Pennsylvania and North Carolina, but these votes were not enough to offset the Democratic-Republican gains elsewhere.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Of the 155 counties and independent cities making returns, Jefferson and Burr won in 115 (74.19%), whereas the Adams ticket carried 40 (25.81%).
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] This was the last time that Vermont voted for the Federalists and the last time a Federalist won electoral votes from Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] This was the first of two elections contested between people who would at some point serve as vice president, the other being 1968.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Of the 16 states that took part in the 1800 election, six (Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Tennessee, and Virginia) used some kind of popular vote.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In Rhode Island and Virginia, voters elected their state's entire Electoral College delegation at large; Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee all used some variation of single-member districts.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In the rest, electors were chosen by the state legislature.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Not until the 1836 presidential election would all states have direct popular selection of electors (except South Carolina, which had its state legislature vote for electors until 1868).
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Popular vote records for several states are incomplete, and the returns from Kentucky and Tennessee appear to have been lost; states did not print or issue electoral ballots, and most were issued by newspapers that supported a particular party or candidate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Newspapers are also the main source of voting records in the early 19th century, and frontier states such as Tennessee had few in operation, without any known surviving examples.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee chose each of their electors from specially-drawn single-member districts, the results from which are as follows.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In February 1801, the members of the House of Representatives balloted as states to determine whether Jefferson or Burr would become president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] There were sixteen states, each with one vote; an absolute majority of nine was required for victory.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] It was the outgoing House of Representatives, controlled by the Federalist Party, that was charged with electing the new president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Jefferson was the great enemy of the Federalists, and a faction of Federalist representatives tried to block him and elect Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Most Federalists voted for Burr, giving Burr six of the eight states controlled by Federalists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The seven delegations controlled by Democratic-Republicans all voted for Jefferson, and Georgia's sole Federalist representative also voted for him, giving him eight states.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The Vermont delegation was evenly split and cast a blank ballot.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The remaining state, Maryland, had five Federalist representatives to three Democratic-Republicans; one of its Federalist representatives voted for Jefferson, forcing that state delegation also to cast a blank ballot.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Publicly, Burr remained quiet between mid-December 1800 and mid-February 1801, when the electoral votes were counted.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Behind the scenes, he faced mounting pressure from within the party to step aside if he and Jefferson should tie in electoral votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Regardless, he refused to disavow the presidency, writing in December 1800 to Representative Samuel Smith (R-MD) that he would not "engage to resign" if chosen president, adding that the question was "unnecessary, unreasonable and impertinent".
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Rumors circulated that Representative James A.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Bayard (F-DE) had—purportedly in Burr's name—approached Smith and Edward Livingston (R-NY) with offers of political appointments if they voted for Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Neither came to pass, however, chiefly due to Hamilton's energetic opposition to Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Hamilton embarked on a frenzied letter-writing campaign to get Federalist Representatives to support Jefferson because he was "by far not so dangerous a man" as Burr; in short, he would much rather have someone with wrong principles than someone devoid of any.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] From February 11 to 17, the House cast a total of 35 ballots; each time eight state delegations voted for Jefferson, one short of the necessary majority of nine.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] On February 17, on the 36th ballot, Bayard changed his vote from Burr to no selection, joined by his allies in Maryland and Vermont.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] This changed the Maryland and Vermont votes from no selection to Jefferson, giving him the votes of 10 states and the presidency.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The four representatives present from South Carolina, all Federalists, also changed their 3–1 selection of Burr to four abstentions.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Due to the experiences of this and the previous election, sentiment for a new way of selecting the president and vice president rose significantly, resulting in the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] In the 2015 musical *Hamilton* by Lin Manuel Miranda, the contest between Jefferson and Burr is recounted in "The Election of 1800".
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The song focuses on Alexander Hamilton's role in deciding the outcome of the 1801 contingent election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] The musical simplifies the complicated multiple elections somewhat, portraying Adams's unpopularity as making the real choice between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] Historians wrote that Adams did not lose that badly in the original election, with the musical inflating the size of Jefferson's victory.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1800-presidential-election] It implies Hamilton's support for Jefferson over Burr was the catalyst for the Burr–Hamilton duel; in fact, while that helped sour relations between Burr and Hamilton, the duel was ultimately provoked by Hamilton's statements about Burr in the 1804 New York gubernatorial election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The **1804 New York gubernatorial election** was held in April 1804 to elect the Governor of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor George Clinton did not run for re-election, having been nominated for Vice President of the United States in February.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In a campaign that blurred partisan divisions, Morgan Lewis defeated Aaron Burr by a landslide margin.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Burr, the incumbent vice president, had been alienated from the Democratic-Republican Party after he challenged Thomas Jefferson in the contested presidential election of 1800.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Though the ascendant Tammany Hall organization and some members of the Federalist Party supported Burr, he was opposed by the bulk of the Republicans, led by the Clinton and Livingston families.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Alexander Hamilton, the most eminent Federalist, also refused to support his personal rival and endorsed Lewis.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Hamilton's longstanding and severe criticisms of Burr, which were published during the campaign, led Burr to challenge him to the duel that killed Hamilton in July 1804.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In the 1800 United States presidential election, Aaron Burr ran on the Republican ticket as the running mate of Thomas Jefferson against incumbent President John Adams of the Federalist Party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] At the time, the Constitution gave each elector two votes for president, and the candidate who received the second most votes became vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The Republican Party planned to have 72 of their 73 electors vote for both Jefferson and Burr, with the remaining elector voting only for Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] However, the electors failed to execute this plan, so Burr and Jefferson tied with 73 votes each.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution stipulated that if two candidates with an Electoral College majority were tied, a contingent election would be held in the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] At the time, the majority of House delegations were controlled by the Federalists, many of whom were loath to vote for their rival Jefferson over the more moderate Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Although Hamilton had a long-standing political rivalry with Jefferson stemming from their tenure as members of George Washington's cabinet, he regarded Burr as more dangerous and used all his influence to ensure Jefferson's election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] On the 36th ballot, the House of Representatives gave Jefferson the presidency, with Burr becoming vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Burr's conduct during the contingent election alienated him permanently from Jefferson and the majority of Republicans, and he returned his focus to state politics, where he engaged in a vicious struggle over political appointments with the Governor's nephew, De Witt Clinton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] At the 1801 constitutional convention, Clinton won a major victory by cementing the exclusive power of the Council of Appointment to nominate and appoint officeholders.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton, who dominated the council, refused to appoint any Burr allies to office.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The political struggle led to mutual recriminations and a duel between Clinton and John Swartwout, in which the latter was shot twice in the leg.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In 1802, De Witt Clinton was elected to the United States Senate; he resigned the next year to become mayor of New York City.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] As the Clinton family became more dominant among the Republicans, Burr grew closer to the Federalist Party and cultivated their support.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton also succeeded in removing Burr and Swartwout from the board of the Manhattan Company in favor of Brockholst Livingston.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] As it became clear that Jefferson would drop Burr from his ticket in the 1804 election, Burr chose to run for Governor of New York instead.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] As Burr's future within the Republican faction faded, New York governor George Clinton rose to fill the power vacuum.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In February 1804, acknowledging the need for a northern running mate, the Republican caucus in Congress nominated Clinton for vice president over John Breckenridge of Kentucky.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] John Lansing Jr. was initially nominated by the Republican caucus in the legislature but declined the nomination on February 18.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] On the same day, a cross-party meeting was held for supporters of Aaron Burr, who nominated him for Governor.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] On February 20, a public meeting was held to approve Burr's nomination in New York City.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] A second meeting was held in Albany to ratify the nomination.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Morgan Lewis, Chief Justice of the Supreme Court, was eventually chosen to replace Lansing, and he was supported by 104 of the 132 members of the Legislature.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The 1804 campaign was among the most vicious in New York history.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The Republicans questioned Burr's private life, while Burr supporters accused the Livingston and Clinton families of packing state offices with relatives.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Alexander Hamilton, whose support of Jefferson in 1801 had been crucial in blocking Burr from the presidency, refused to join the majority of Federalists in supporting Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] During the campaign, private attacks by Hamilton on Burr's character were made public.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Lewis defeated Burr by the widest margin in New York history to that point.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Blaming Hamilton for his defeats in both 1801 and 1804, Burr charged Hamilton with a smear campaign through the intentional dissemination of his private comments.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Hamilton refused to acknowledge the accusation, but accepted when Burr challenged him to a duel.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] On July 11, 1804, Burr and Hamilton met in Weehawken, New Jersey; when the signal was given, Burr shot instantly, striking Hamilton in the chest.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Hamilton's death ended Burr's political future in New York and weakened the already-waning Federalist Party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Burr left New York for the American West but was arrested in 1807 on charges of treason for his involvement in an alleged plot to lead a secessionist movement.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] After his acquittal, Burr entered a self-imposed exile to Europe before returning to New York City to live out his life as an attorney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-new-york-gubernatorial-election] With Hamilton dead and Burr sidelined, the Clinton and Livingston families expected uncontested control of state politics after 1804.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1804.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party's ticket of incumbent president Thomas Jefferson and former New York governor George Clinton defeated the Federalist Party's ticket of former U.S. minister to France Charles Cotesworth Pinckney and former U.S. minister to the United Kingdom Rufus King.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election held under the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which required separate ballots for president and vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was unanimously renominated by his party's congressional nominating caucus in February; the caucus selected Clinton to succeed the outgoing vice president, Aaron Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] A "semisecret" Federalist caucus elevated Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates; while news of the caucus was widely circulated, in states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists in several states chose not to nominate electors, resulting in a lopsided popular vote margin for Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was widely popular and considered unbeatable by many observers, following his narrow election four years earlier.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Economic prosperity, the expansion of voting rights, and the disorganized state of the opposition all benefited his campaign.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists portrayed Jefferson as a demagogue for his embrace of populist, democratic politics, and a dictator for his use of patronage and reforms to the federal judiciary.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's complicity in slavery did little to damage his candidacy even in New England, where he carried the Federalist stronghold of Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two electoral districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received the electoral votes of Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were appointed by the legislature, and two votes from unpledged electors in Maryland.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson polled more than 106,000 popular votes, representing 73 percent of the total, compared with fewer than 40,000 votes for the Federalist electors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent Federalist president John Adams sought re-election in 1800, but was defeated by Democratic-Republican challenger Thomas Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's running mate, Aaron Burr, was elected vice president following a contingent election in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The right to vote was widespread in the United States during the Early Republic, including the large majority of adult white men.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The expansion of voting rights during Jefferson's first term included the establishment of universal white male suffrage in Maryland in 1801.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Propertied, single women retained the right to vote in New Jersey, while Black men who met all other property and taxpaying requirements were eligible in New England, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Tennessee.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most places, voting was by secret ballot.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] (Kentucky and Virginia retained the English custom of oral voting.) Eligible individuals voted using paper tickets, typically handwritten, listing the voter's choice for the various offices.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Enforcement of property and taxpaying qualifications was generally lax, in part due to the frequency of land sales, which outpaced officials' ability to keep accurate records of ownership.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In other cases, local opinion or the threat of rioting might compel election officials to permit veterans and small landholders to vote when otherwise disenfranchised by state law.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congress passed the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which was ratified by the states prior to the election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Amendment instructed the United States Electoral College to elect the president and vice president on separate ballots.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists opposed ratifying the Amendment, hoping to exploit the original electoral system to sow discord in the Democratic-Republican ranks.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign, some Federalists encouraged the Democratic-Republican electors from New York to support Clinton for president over Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Efforts to delay ratification of the Amendment were unsuccessful, and the new system took effect in September 1804 in time for the election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson faced no internal opposition to his bid for re-election; the Democratic-Republican congressional caucus nominated him unanimously on February 25.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] With Burr out of the running, the selection of the vice-presidential candidate was the caucus's main responsibility.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] George Clinton and John Breckinridge were the leading contenders for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton had served as governor of New York for most of the last thirty years and was a veteran of the American Revolutionary War; he had received 50 electoral votes in the 1792 United States presidential election, and declined a place on the Democratic-Republican ticket in 1800.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although of advanced age, his political views aligned with Jefferson's, and he remained popular with Democratic-Republicans in his home state.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge, a Kentuckian, was the choice of Western Democratic-Republicans concerned with regional representation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other candidates included the U.S. attorney general, Levi Lincoln Sr.; the former U.S. senator from New Hampshire, John Langdon; and the U.S. postmaster general, Gideon Granger.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas McKean was discussed as a possible contender, but withdrew prior to the caucus.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 110 Democratic-Republican members of Congress.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton won the nomination with 67 votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Federalists did not meet formally to nominate a ticket, as they had done in the previous election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party was ill-prepared to mount a national campaign, and few believed Jefferson could be defeated.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, a "semisecret caucus" in Washington proposed Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates on February 22.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although this meeting was widely reported, significant uncertainty persisted concerning the identities of the Federalist candidates throughout the campaign.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist electors remained formally unpledged.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans established a vast network of state, county, town, and ward committees to conduct the campaign.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states such as Ohio, the overriding importance of the presidential election was an agent of party unity.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republicans organized celebrations to commemorate the anniversary of Jefferson's first inauguration on March 4 and the Louisiana Purchase on May 11.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Parades, dinners, and toasting were the mainstays of such events.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Supporters sang campaign songs such as "Jefferson and Liberty," written to commemorate the last election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican militia units, professional associations, benevolent societies, and partisan groups like the Young Men of Democratic Principles were visible supporters of the president's re-election campaign.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans made effective use of the partisan press.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party's national paper, the *National Intelligencer*, was widely circulated and supported a vast array of state and local print publications.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican campaign catered to the nation's developing white male democracy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The abandonment of property requirements for voting in Maryland and New Jersey benefited Jefferson, whose economic policies were considered favorable to working people.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican newspapers and broadsides were written in plain language accessible to the average person.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The themes of "simplicity and frugality" and equality of opportunity were central to the party's appeal to voters, contrasted against Federalist elitism.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In contrast to the Democratic-Republicans, the Federalists entered the campaign demoralized and to some degree leaderless.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney displayed little interest in the election and devoted most of 1804 to a local campaign against dueling.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party lost its most influential leader in July, when Alexander Hamilton was killed in a duel by the outgoing vice president, Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's former deputy, Timothy Pickering, saw no hope for the presidential election and instead advocated for New England to secede from the United States.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other Federalists simply withdrew from politics rather than endure a seemingly inevitable defeat.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard, advocated for the party to update its tactics.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The growth of mass politics in the early nineteenth century made the Federalists' reliance on elite relationships increasingly obsolete.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists held celebrations on the anniversary of Washington's birthday and organized groups like the Washington Benevolent Societies.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The effectiveness of the party press was hindered by the stilted, formal style of many Federalist newspapers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of Jefferson, rather than enthusiasm for Pinckney, characterized the Federalist campaign.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the party nominated electors, its ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist press generally avoided mention of Pinckney and King; the Boston *Columbian Centinel* denied that the Federalist electors were pledged to Pinckney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Dauer argues that the uncertainty surrounding the Federalist ticket cost the party the electoral votes of Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists described Jefferson as an aspiring dictator.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] They compared the Louisiana Purchase to Napoleon's European conquests and accused Jefferson of violating the Constitution, which did not specify the president's power to acquire new territory.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Increasingly, Federalists saw parallels between Jefferson's administration and the rule of European tyrants, including Napoleon, Maximilien Robespierre, and Julius Caesar.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's use of patronage and the impeachment of Samuel Chase by the House of Representatives in March 1804 were criticized by Federalists who feared Jefferson's growing influence over the political system.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The repeal of the Midnight Judges Act and the reduction of the United States Armed Forces were cast as attempts to dismantle the federal government of the United States.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's sexual relationship with Sally Hemings, an enslaved woman and the half-sister of his late wife, Martha Jefferson, was first exposed by James T.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had six children with Hemings between 1795 and 1808, although some historians argue their relationship began much earlier, during Jefferson's tenure as the U.S. minister to France.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists seized on the scandal to attack Jefferson's hypocrisy and personal character.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Partisan journals printed doggerel mocking Jefferson's promiscuity with verses that emphasized Hemings's race and complexion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In pillorying Jefferson as an enslaver, Federalist writers did not intend to critique social inequality; instead, they sought to use Jefferson's complicity in slavery to discredit democratic politics.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists attacked Jefferson's religious views, which they described as atheism.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist ministers characterized the Democratic-Republican Party as a grave threat to Christianity.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's economic policies catered to the interests of free men and entrepreneurs, in contrast to Federalist policies that prioritized wealthy creditors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Joyce Appleby argues that Jefferson's laissez-faire posture facilitated commercial expansion that benefited white men regardless of class.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Whereas the Federalists used economic regulation to promote the interests of creditors, Democratic-Republicans favored a decentralized economy in which opportunities to participate in commerce were more broadly accessible.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists interpreted Democratic-Republican policies as an attack on elite privilege and defended the principle of economic inequality.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although many Democratic-Republicans were skeptical of national corporations, corporations and banks flourished at the state and local level.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both Jefferson and Pinckney were enslavers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney played a critical role in the adoption of the Three-Fifths Clause by the Constitutional Convention and opposed the efforts to end the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson criticized slavery in print, but did little either privately or politically to diminish it; as president, he withheld diplomatic recognition from the First Empire of Haiti, the first independent state in the Americas established as the result of a successful slave rebellion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attempted to make slavery an issue in New England, with limited success.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both national parties sought to avoid discussion of slavery during the 1790s; after 1801, the decline of the Federalist Party in the Southern United States freed Northern Federalists to attack slavery more directly.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Antislavery rhetoric featured in some Federalists' critiques of the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists demanded the repeal of the Three-Fifths Clause, which disadvantaged the region in terms of congressional apportionment.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] These appeals largely failed to motivate opposition to Jefferson, while accompanying calls for secession met with little popular support.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of the Three-Fifths Clause emphasized New England Federalists' partisan self-interest.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Many Federalists blamed this provision for their defeat in the last election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Fisher Ames wrote that "black votes" had elected Jefferson in 1800 and that the administration therefore lacked a popular mandate.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists frequently pointed to prominent Democratic-Republicans' complicity in slavery as evidence of the party's hypocrisy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Opposing political rights for both white and Black workers, they pointed to the contradictions in Jeffersonian democracy as proof that a political system based on mass participation was unworkable.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists appeared to win the popular vote on Election Day in North Carolina's Fayetteville district, but the exclusion of the return from Montgomery County, North Carolina, subsequently gave the district's single electoral vote to Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson carried Massachusetts and New Hampshire, as well as seven of nine Maryland districts.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, Jefferson carried every county except Adams, where a last-minute Federalist effort narrowly succeeded in keeping the county out of the Democratic-Republican column.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Ohio Federalists' attempt to split the Democratic-Republican Party was unsuccessful, and the Jefferson electors defeated the Federalist ticket by a wide margin.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists did not contest the remaining popular vote states, but unpledged electors received write-in votes in New Jersey and Virginia.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received electoral votes from Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were chosen by the state legislature, while Jefferson swept the remaining states for a total of 162 electoral votes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Jefferson was the first of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Henry Clay, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, Cleveland, Roosevelt, and Trump were also their respective party's nominees for three consecutive elections.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Nineteenth-century election laws required voters to elect the members of the Electoral College individually, rather than as a block.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This sometimes resulted in small differences in the number of votes cast for electors pledged to the same presidential nominee, if some voters did not vote for all the electors nominated by a party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table compares the votes for the most popular elector on each ticket.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In the single-member districts in Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee, the result is the sum of all votes for electors pledged to one nominee.
[src:alexander-hamilton/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, where several distinct anti-Jefferson tickets ran in different parts of the state, the result shown is the sum of the votes for the leading electors in each county.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Born out of wedlock in Charlestown on the Caribbean island of Nevis, Hamilton was orphaned as a child and taken in by a prosperous merchant.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He was given a scholarship and pursued his education at King's College (now Columbia University) in New York City where, despite his young age, he was an anonymous but prolific and widely read pamphleteer and advocate for the American Revolution.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] After the Revolutionary War, Hamilton served as a delegate from New York to the Congress of the Confederation in Philadelphia.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He resigned to practice law and founded the Bank of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In 1786, Hamilton led the Annapolis Convention, which sought to strengthen the power of the loose confederation of independent states under the limited authorities granted the Congress by the Articles of Confederation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The following year he was a delegate to the Philadelphia Convention, which drafted the U.S.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Constitution creating a more centralized federal national government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He then authored 51 of the 85 installments of *The Federalist Papers*, which proved persuasive in securing its ratification by the states and remains the preeminent interpretation of Constitutional intent.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] As a trusted member of President Washington's first cabinet, Hamilton served as the first U.S. secretary of the treasury.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He envisioned a central government led by an energetic executive, a strong national defense, and a more diversified economy with significantly expanded industry.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He successfully argued that the implied powers of the U.S.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Constitution provided the legal basis to create the First Bank of the United States, and assume the states' war debts, which was funded by a tariff on imports and a whiskey tax.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton opposed American entanglement with the succession of unstable French revolutionary governments.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Revenue Cutter Service to protect American shipping.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In 1793, he advocated in support of the Jay Treaty under which the U.S. resumed friendly trade relations with the British Empire.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton's views became the basis for the Federalist Party, which was opposed by the Democratic-Republican Party, led by Thomas Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton and other Federalists supported the Haitian Revolution, and Hamilton helped draft Haiti's constitution in 1801.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] After resigning as the nation's secretary of the treasury in 1795, Hamilton resumed his legal and business activities and helped lead the abolition of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In the Quasi-War, fought at sea between 1798 and 1800, Hamilton called for mobilization against France, and President John Adams appointed him major general.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Army, however, did not see combat in the conflict.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Outraged by Adams' response to the crisis, Hamilton opposed his 1800 presidential re-election.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Jefferson and Aaron Burr tied for the presidency in the electoral college and, despite philosophical differences, Hamilton endorsed Jefferson over Burr, whom he found unprincipled.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] When Burr ran for Governor of New York in 1804, Hamilton again opposed his candidacy, arguing that he was unfit for the office.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Taking offense, Burr challenged Hamilton to a pistol duel, which took place in Weehawken, New Jersey, on July 11, 1804.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton was mortally wounded and immediately transported back across the Hudson River in a delirious state to the home of William Bayard Jr. in Greenwich Village, New York, for medical attention.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The following day, on July 12, 1804, Hamilton succumbed to his wounds.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Scholars generally regard Hamilton as an astute and intellectually brilliant administrator, politician, and financier who was sometimes impetuous.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] His ideas are credited with influencing the founding principles of American finance and government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton was born on January 11, 1755, or 1757, in Charlestown, the capital of Nevis in the British Leeward Islands, where he spent his childhood.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton and his older brother, James Jr., were born out of wedlock to Rachel Lavien (née Faucette), a married woman of half-British and half-Huguenot descent, and James A.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton, a Scotsman and the fourth son of Alexander Hamilton, the laird of Grange, Ayrshire.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] His maternal grandfather was John Faucette (born c.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] 1680–1684), a French Huguenot, planter and medical doctor born in the Saintonge province of France who had settled on the British west indies island of Nevis, after the 1685 Revocation of the Edict of Nantes by Louis XIV.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Prior to Alexander's birth, in 1745, Rachel Lavien married Johann Lavien in Saint Croix.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] However, Rachel Lavien left her husband and first son in 1750, traveling to Saint Kitts, where she met James Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton and Lavien moved together to Nevis, her birthplace, where she had inherited a seaside lot in town from her father.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] While their mother was living, Alexander and James Jr. received individual tutoring and classes in a private school led by a Jewish headmistress.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Alexander supplemented his education with a family library of 34 books.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Both his mother and Hamilton contracted yellow fever.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] On February 19, 1768, Hamilton's mother died from the disease, leaving him orphaned.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In probate court, Lavien's "first husband seized her estate" and obtained the few valuables that she had owned, including some household silver.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Many items were auctioned off, and a friend purchased the family's books, returning them to Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The brothers were briefly taken in by their cousin Peter Lytton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] However, Lytton took his own life in July 1769, leaving his property to his mistress and their son, and the propertyless Hamilton brothers were subsequently separated.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] James Jr. apprenticed with a local carpenter, while Alexander was given a home by Thomas Stevens, a merchant from Nevis.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton became a clerk at Beekman and Cruger, a local import-export firm that traded with the Province of New York and New England.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Though still a teenager, Hamilton proved capable enough as a trader to be left in charge of the firm for five months in 1771 while the owner was at sea.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He remained an avid reader, and later developed an interest in writing and a life outside Saint Croix.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He wrote a detailed letter to his father regarding a hurricane that devastated Christiansted on August 30, 1772.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In October 1772, Hamilton arrived by ship in Boston and then proceeded to New York City, where he boarded with Hercules Mulligan, the Irish-born brother of a trader known to Hamilton's benefactors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Mulligan assisted Hamilton in selling the cargo that Hamilton was to use to pay for his education and support.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton sought to fill gaps in his education in preparation for college, and later that year began to attend Elizabethtown Academy, a preparatory school run by Francis Barber in Elizabeth, New Jersey.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] While there, he was introduced to William Livingston, a local leading intellectual and revolutionary who influenced him, and he boarded with the Livingstons while studying.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In fall 1773, Hamilton returned to New York and entered Mulligan's alma mater, King's College (now Columbia University).
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton began as a private student and boarded again with Mulligan until he matriculated into the college the following year, in May 1774.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] His college roommate and lifelong friend Robert Troup spoke glowingly of Hamilton's clarity in concisely explaining the Patriot case against the British during the American Revolution in what was Hamilton's first public appearance, on July 6, 1774.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] As King's College students, Hamilton, Troup, and four other undergraduates formed an unnamed literary society that is regarded as a precursor to what is now the Philolexian Society.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Later in 1774, Church of England clergyman Samuel Seabury in New York published a series of pamphlets promoting the Loyalist cause, seeking to provoke fear in the Thirteen Colonies, which he hoped would discourage them from uniting against the British.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton supported the revolutionary cause before the war began, but he disapproved of mob violence against the Loyalists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] On May 10, 1775, he was credited with saving King's College president Myles Cooper, a Loyalist, from an angry mob by speaking to the crowd long enough to allow Cooper to escape.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton was forced to discontinue his studies before graduating when the college closed its doors during the British occupation of New York City and his subsequent military service.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton drilled with the company before classes in the graveyard of nearby St.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Paul's Chapel, studied military history and tactics on his own, and was soon elected an officer.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Under fire from HMS *Asia*, and coordinating with Hercules Mulligan and the Sons of Liberty, he led his newly renamed unit, the "Hearts of Oak," on a successful raid for British cannons in the Battery.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The seizure of the cannons resulted in the unit being re-designated an artillery company.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Through his connections with influential New York patriots, including Alexander McDougall and John Jay, Hamilton was commissioned by the revolutionary government to raise the New York Provincial Company of Artillery of 60 men in 1776, and was then appointed captain.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The company took part in the campaign of 1776 in and around New York City; as rearguard of the Continental Army's retreat up Manhattan, serving at the Battle of Harlem Heights shortly after, and at the Battle of White Plains a month later.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] At the Battle of Trenton, the company was stationed at the high point of town at the intersection of present-day Warren and Broad streets to keep the Hessians pinned down in their barracks.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton participated in the Battle of Princeton on January 3, 1777.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] After an initial setback, Washington rallied the Continental Army troops and led them in a successful charge against the British forces.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] After making a brief stand, the British fell back, some leaving Princeton, and others taking up refuge in Nassau Hall.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton transported three cannons to the hall, and had them fire upon the building as others rushed the front door and broke it down.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The British subsequently put a white flag outside one of the windows; 194 British soldiers walked out of the building and laid down their arms, ending the battle in an American victory.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton was invited to become an aide to Continental Army general William Alexander, Lord Stirling, and another general, perhaps Nathanael Greene or Alexander McDougall.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He declined these invitations, believing his best chance for improving his station in life was glory on the Revolutionary War's battlefields.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton eventually received an invitation he felt he could not refuse: to serve as George Washington's aide with the rank of lieutenant colonel.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton served four years as Washington's chief staff aide.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He handled letters to the Continental Congress, state governors, and the most powerful generals of the Continental Army.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He drafted many of Washington's orders and letters under Washington's direction, and he eventually issued orders on Washington's behalf over his own signature.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton was involved in a wide variety of high-level duties, including intelligence, diplomacy, and negotiation with senior army officers as Washington's emissary.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] While stationed at the army's winter headquarters in Morristown, New Jersey from December 1779 to March 1780, Hamilton met Elizabeth Schuyler, a daughter of General Philip Schuyler and Catherine Van Rensselaer.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] They married on December 14, 1780, at the Schuyler Mansion in Albany, New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] They had eight children, Philip, Angelica, Alexander, James, John, William, Eliza, and another Philip.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] During the Revolutionary War, Hamilton became the close friend of several fellow officers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] His letters to the Marquis de Lafayette and to John Laurens, employing the sentimental literary conventions of the late 18th century and alluding to Greek history and mythology, have been read by Jonathan Ned Katz as revelatory of a homosocial or even homosexual relationship.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Massey amongst others, by contrast, dismisses all such speculation as unsubstantiated, describing their friendship as purely platonic camaraderie instead and placing their correspondence in the context of the flowery diction of the time.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] While on Washington's staff, Hamilton long sought command and a return to active combat.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] As the war drew nearer to an end, he knew that opportunities for military glory were diminishing.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] On February 15, 1781, Hamilton was reprimanded by Washington after a minor misunderstanding.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Although Washington quickly tried to mend their relationship, Hamilton insisted on leaving his staff.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He officially left in March, and settled with his new wife Elizabeth Schuyler close to Washington's headquarters.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He continued to repeatedly ask Washington and others for a field command.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Washington continued to demur, citing the need to appoint men of higher rank.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] On July 31, Washington relented and assigned Hamilton as commander of a battalion of light infantry companies of the 1st and 2nd New York Regiments and two provisional companies from Connecticut.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In the planning for the assault on Yorktown, Hamilton was given command of three battalions, which were to fight in conjunction with the allied French troops in taking Redoubts No.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] 10 of the British fortifications at Yorktown.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton and his battalions took Redoubt No.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] 10 with bayonets alone so as not to risk accidental gunfire and discovery in a nighttime action, as planned.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The French also suffered heavy casualties and took Redoubt No.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] These actions led to the surrender of the besieged British army at Yorktown, marking the *de facto* end of the war, although small battles continued for two more years until the signing of the Treaty of Paris and the departure of the last British troops.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] After Yorktown, Hamilton returned to New York City and resigned his commission in March 1782.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He passed the bar in July after six months of self-directed education and, in October, was licensed to argue cases before the Supreme Court of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He also accepted an offer from Robert Morris to become receiver of continental taxes for the New York state.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton was appointed in July 1782 to the Congress of the Confederation as a New York representative for the term beginning in November 1782.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Before his appointment to Congress in 1782, Hamilton was already sharing his criticisms of Congress.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] While on Washington's staff, Hamilton had become frustrated with the decentralized nature of the wartime Continental Congress, particularly its dependence upon the states for voluntary financial support that was not often forthcoming.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Under the Articles of Confederation, Congress had no power to collect taxes or to demand money from the states.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] This lack of a stable source of funding had made it difficult for the Continental Army both to obtain its necessary provisions and to pay its soldiers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] During the war, and for some time after, Congress obtained what funds it could from subsidies from the King of France, European loans, and aid requested from the several states, which were often unable or unwilling to contribute.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] James Madison joined Hamilton in influencing Congress to send a delegation to persuade Rhode Island to change its mind.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Their report recommending the delegation argued the national government needed not just some level of financial autonomy, but also the ability to make laws that superseded those of the individual states.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton transmitted a letter arguing that Congress already had the power to tax, since it had the power to fix the sums due from the several states; but Virginia's rescission of its own ratification of this amendment ended the Rhode Island negotiations.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] While Hamilton was in Congress, discontented soldiers began to pose a danger to the young United States.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Most of the army was then posted at Newburgh, New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Those in the army were funding much of their own supplies, and they had not been paid in eight months.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Furthermore, after Valley Forge, the Continental officers had been promised in May 1778 a pension of half their pay when they were discharged.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] By the early 1780s, due to the structure of the government under the Articles of Confederation, it had no power to tax to either raise revenue or pay its soldiers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In 1782, after several months without pay, a group of officers organized to send a delegation to lobby Congress, led by Captain Alexander McDougall.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The officers had three demands: the army's pay, their own pensions, and commutation of those pensions into a lump-sum payment if Congress were unable to afford the half-salary pensions for life.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Several congressmen, including Hamilton, Robert Morris, and Gouverneur Morris, attempted to use the so-called Newburgh Conspiracy as leverage to secure support from the states and in Congress for funding of the national government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton suggested using the Army's claims to prevail upon the states for the proposed national funding system.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The Morrises and Hamilton contacted General Henry Knox to suggest he and the officers defy civil authority, at least by not disbanding if the army were not satisfied.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton wrote Washington to suggest that Hamilton covertly "take direction" of the officers' efforts to secure redress, to secure continental funding but keep the army within the limits of moderation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Washington wrote Hamilton back, declining to introduce the army.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] After the crisis had ended, Washington warned of the dangers of using the army as leverage to gain support for the national funding plan.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] On March 15, Washington defused the Newburgh situation by addressing the officers personally.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Congress ordered the Army officially disbanded in April 1783.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In the same month, Congress passed a new measure for a 25-year impost—which Hamilton voted against—that again required the consent of all the states; it also approved a commutation of the officers' pensions to five years of full pay.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Rhode Island again opposed these provisions, and Hamilton's robust assertions of national prerogatives in his previous letter were widely held to be excessive.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In June 1783, a different group of disgruntled soldiers from Lancaster, Pennsylvania, sent Congress a petition demanding their back pay.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] When they began to march toward Philadelphia, Congress charged Hamilton and two others with intercepting the mob.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton requested militia from Pennsylvania's Supreme Executive Council, but was turned down.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton instructed Assistant Secretary of War William Jackson to intercept the men.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The mob arrived in Philadelphia, and the soldiers proceeded to harangue Congress for their pay.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton argued that Congress ought to adjourn to Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Frustrated with the weakness of the national government, Hamilton while in Princeton, drafted a call to revise the Articles of Confederation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] This resolution contained many features of the future Constitution of the United States, including a strong federal government with the ability to collect taxes and raise an army.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] It also included the separation of powers into the legislative, executive, and judicial branches.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton resigned from Congress in 1783.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] When the British left New York in 1783, he practiced there in partnership with Richard Harison.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He specialized in defending Tories and British subjects, as in *Rutgers v.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Waddington*, in which he defeated a claim for damages done to a brewery by the Englishmen who held it during the military occupation of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He pleaded for the mayor's court to interpret state law consistent with the 1783 Treaty of Paris, which had ended the Revolutionary War.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In 1784, Hamilton founded the Bank of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Long dissatisfied with the Articles of Confederation as too weak to be effective, Hamilton played a major leadership role at the 1786 Annapolis Convention.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He drafted its resolution for a constitutional convention, and in doing so brought one step closer to reality his longtime desire to have a more effectual, more financially self-sufficient federal government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] As a member of the legislature of New York, Hamilton argued forcefully and at length in favor of a bill to recognize the sovereignty of the State of Vermont, against numerous objections to its constitutionality and policy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Consideration of the bill was deferred to a later date.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] From 1787 to 1789, Hamilton exchanged letters with Nathaniel Chipman, a lawyer representing Vermont.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] After the Constitution of the United States went into effect, Hamilton said, "One of the first subjects of deliberation with the new Congress will be the independence of Kentucky, for which the southern states will be anxious.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The northern will be glad to send a counterpoise in Vermont." Vermont was admitted to the Union in 1791.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In 1788, he was awarded a Master of Arts degree from his alma mater, the former King's College, now reconstituted as Columbia College.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] It was during this post-war period that Hamilton served on the college's board of trustees, playing a part in the reopening of the college and placing it on firm financial footing.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] In 1787, Hamilton served as assemblyman from New York County in the New York State Legislature and was chosen as a delegate at the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia by his father-in-law Philip Schuyler.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Even though Hamilton had been a leader in calling for a new Constitutional Convention, his direct influence at the Convention itself was quite limited.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Governor George Clinton's faction in the New York legislature had chosen New York's other two delegates, John Lansing Jr. and Robert Yates, and both of them opposed Hamilton's goal of a strong national government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Thus, whenever the other two members of the New York delegation were present, they decided New York's vote, to ensure that there were no major alterations to the Articles of Confederation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Early in the convention, Hamilton made a speech proposing a president-for-life; it had no effect upon the deliberations of the convention.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He proposed to have an elected president and elected senators who would serve for life, contingent upon "good behavior" and subject to removal for corruption or abuse; this idea contributed later to the hostile view of Hamilton as a monarchist sympathizer, held by James Madison.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] According to Madison's notes, Hamilton said in regards to the executive, "The English model was the only good one on this subject.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The hereditary interest of the king was so interwoven with that of the nation, and his personal emoluments so great, that he was placed above the danger of being corrupted from abroad...
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton argued, "And let me observe that an executive is less dangerous to the liberties of the people when in office during life than for seven years.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] It may be said this constitutes as an elective monarchy ...
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] But by making the executive subject to impeachment, the term 'monarchy' cannot apply ..." In his notes of the convention, Madison interpreted Hamilton's proposal as claiming power for the "rich and well born".
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Madison's perspective all but isolated Hamilton from his fellow delegates and others who felt they did not reflect the ideas of revolution and liberty.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] During the convention, Hamilton constructed a draft for the Constitution based on the convention debates, but he never presented it.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] This draft had most of the features of the actual Constitution.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The president would have an absolute veto.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The Supreme Court was to have immediate jurisdiction over all lawsuits involving the United States, and state governors were to be appointed by the federal government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] At the end of the convention, Hamilton was still not content with the final Constitution, but signed it anyway as a vast improvement over the Articles of Confederation, and urged his fellow delegates to do so also.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Since the other two members of the New York delegation, Lansing and Yates, had already withdrawn, Hamilton was the only New York signer to the United States Constitution.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He then took a highly active part in the successful campaign for the document's ratification in New York in 1788, which was a crucial step in its national ratification.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He first used the popularity of the Constitution by the masses to compel George Clinton to sign, but was unsuccessful.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The state convention in Poughkeepsie in June 1788 pitted Hamilton, Jay, James Duane, Robert Livingston, and Richard Morris against the Clintonian faction led by Melancton Smith, Lansing, Yates, and Gilbert Livingston.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Clinton's faction wanted to amend the Constitution, while maintaining the state's right to secede if their attempts failed, and members of Hamilton's faction were against any conditional ratification, under the impression that New York would not be accepted into the Union.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] During the state convention, New Hampshire and Virginia becoming the ninth and tenth states to ratify the Constitution, respectively, had ensured any adjournment would not happen and a compromise would have to be reached.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton's arguments used for the ratifications were largely iterations of work from *The Federalist Papers*, and Smith eventually went for ratification, though it was more out of necessity than Hamilton's rhetoric.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The vote in the state convention was ratified 30 to 27, on July 26, 1788.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton recruited John Jay and James Madison to write *The Federalist Papers*, a series of essays, to defend the proposed Constitution.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] He made the largest contribution to that effort, writing 51 of the 85 essays published.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton supervised the entire project, enlisted the participants, wrote the majority of the essays, and oversaw the publication.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] During the project, each person was responsible for their areas of expertise.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Madison covered the history of republics and confederacies, along with the anatomy of the new government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton covered the branches of government most pertinent to him: the executive and judicial branches, with some aspects of the Senate, as well as covering military matters and taxation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] The papers first appeared in *The Independent Journal* on October 27, 1787.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton wrote the first paper signed as Publius, and all of the subsequent papers were signed under the name.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Jay wrote the next four papers to elaborate on the confederation's weakness and the need for unity against foreign aggression and against splitting into rival confederacies, and, except for No.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton also wrote an extensive defense of the constitution (No.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] 23–36), and discussed the Senate and executive and judicial branches (No.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Hamilton and Madison worked to describe the anarchic state of the confederation (No.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] 15–22), and the two have been described as not being significantly different in thought during this time period—in contrast to their stark opposition later in life.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p01] Subtle differences appeared with the two when discussing the necessity of standing armies.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In 1789, Washington—who had become the first president of the United States—appointed Hamilton to be his cabinet's secretary of the treasury on the advice of Robert Morris, Washington's initial pick.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] On September 11, 1789, Hamilton was nominated and confirmed in the Senate and sworn in the same day as the first United States secretary of the treasury.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Before the adjournment of the House in September 1789, they requested Hamilton to make a report on suggestions to improve the public credit by January 1790.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton had written to Morris as early as 1781, that fixing the public credit will win their objective of independence.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The sources that Hamilton used ranged from Frenchmen such as Jacques Necker and Montesquieu to British writers such as Hume, Hobbes, and Malachy Postlethwayt.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] While writing the report he also sought out suggestions from contemporaries such as John Witherspoon and Madison.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Although they agreed on additional taxes such as distilleries and duties on imported liquors and land taxes, Madison feared that the securities from the government debt would fall into foreign hands.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton divided the debt into national and state, and further divided the national debt into foreign and domestic debt.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] While there was agreement on how to handle the foreign debt, especially with France, there was not with regards to the national debt held by domestic creditors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] During the Revolutionary War, affluent citizens had invested in bonds, and war veterans had been paid with promissory notes and IOUs that plummeted in price during the Confederation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In response, the war veterans sold the securities to speculators for as little as fifteen to twenty cents on the dollar.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton felt the money from the bonds should not go to the soldiers who had shown little faith in the country's future, but the speculators that had bought the bonds from the soldiers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The process of attempting to track down the original bondholders along with the government showing discrimination among the classes of holders if the war veterans were to be compensated also weighed in as factors for Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] As for the state debts, Hamilton suggested consolidating them with the national debt and label it as federal debt, for the sake of efficiency on a national scale.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In the report, Hamilton felt that the securities should be paid at full value to their legitimate owners, including those who took the financial risk of buying government bonds that most experts thought would never be redeemed.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He argued that liberty and property security were inseparable, and that the government should honor the contracts, as they formed the basis of public and private morality.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] To Hamilton, the proper handling of the government debt would also allow America to borrow at affordable interest rates and would also be a stimulant to the economy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The last portion of the report dealt with eliminating the debt by utilizing a *sinking fund* that would retire five percent of the debt annually until it was paid off.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Due to the bonds being traded well below their face value, the purchases would benefit the government as the securities rose in price.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] When the report was submitted to the House of Representatives, detractors soon began to speak against it.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Some of the negative views expressed in the House were that the notion of programs that resembled British practice were wicked, and that the balance of power would be shifted away from the representatives to the executive branch.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] William Maclay suspected that several congressmen were involved in government securities, seeing Congress in an unholy league with New York speculators.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Congressman James Jackson also spoke against New York, with allegations of speculators attempting to swindle those who had not yet heard about Hamilton's report.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The involvement of those in Hamilton's circle such as Schuyler, William Duer, James Duane, Gouverneur Morris, and Rufus King as speculators was not favorable to those against the report, either, though Hamilton personally did not own or deal a share in the debt.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Madison eventually spoke against it by February 1790.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Although he was not against current holders of government debt to profit, he wanted the windfall to go to the original holders.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Madison did not feel that the original holders had lost faith in the government but sold their securities out of desperation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The compromise was seen as egregious to both Hamiltonians and their dissidents such as Maclay, and Madison's vote was defeated 36 votes to 13 on February 22.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The fight for the national government to assume state debt was a longer issue and lasted over four months.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Duer resigned as Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, and the vote of assumption was voted down 31 votes to 29 on April 12.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] During this period, Hamilton bypassed the rising issue of slavery in Congress, after Quakers petitioned for its abolition, returning to the issue the following year.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Another issue in which Hamilton played a role was the temporary location of the capital from New York City.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Tench Coxe was sent to speak to Maclay to bargain about the capital being temporarily located to Philadelphia, as a single vote in the Senate was needed and five in the House for the bill to pass.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The bill passed in the Senate on July 21 and in the House 34 votes to 28 on July 26, 1790.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's *Report on a National Bank* was a projection from the first *Report on the Public Credit*.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Although Hamilton had been forming ideas of a national bank as early as 1779, he had gathered ideas in various ways over the past eleven years.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] These included theories from Adam Smith, extensive studies on the Bank of England, the blunders of the Bank of North America and his experience in establishing the Bank of New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He also used American records from James Wilson, Pelatiah Webster, Gouverneur Morris, and from his assistant treasury secretary Tench Coxe.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He thought that this plan for a National Bank could help in any sort of financial crisis.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton suggested that Congress should charter the national bank with a capitalization of $10 million, one-fifth of which would be handled by the government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Since the government did not have the money, it would borrow the money from the bank itself, and repay the loan in ten even annual installments.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The rest was to be available to individual investors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The bank was to be governed by a twenty-five-member board of directors that was to represent a large majority of the private shareholders, which Hamilton considered essential for his being under a private direction.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The tax revenue to initiate the bank was the same as he had previously proposed, increases on imported spirits: rum, liquor, and whiskey.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The bill passed through the Senate practically without a problem, but objections to the proposal increased by the time it reached the House of Representatives.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] It was generally held by critics that Hamilton was serving the interests of the Northeast by means of the bank, and those of the agrarian lifestyle would not benefit from it.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Among those critics was James Jackson of Georgia, who also attempted to refute the report by quoting from *The Federalist Papers*.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Madison and Jefferson also opposed the bank bill.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The potential of the capital not being moved to the Potomac if the bank was to have a firm establishment in Philadelphia was a more significant reason, and actions that Pennsylvania members of Congress took to keep the capital there made both men anxious.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] *The Whiskey Rebellion* also showed how in other financial plans, there was a distance between the classes as the wealthy profited from the taxes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Madison warned the Pennsylvania congress members that he would attack the bill as unconstitutional in the House, and followed up on his threat.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Madison argued his case of where the power of a bank could be established within the Constitution, but he failed to sway members of the House, and his authority on the constitution was questioned by a few members.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The bill eventually passed in an overwhelming fashion 39 to 20, on February 8, 1791.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Washington hesitated to sign the bill, as he received suggestions from Attorney General Edmund Randolph and Thomas Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In response to the objection of the clause, Hamilton stated that "Necessary often means no more than needful, requisite, incidental, useful, or conductive to", and the bank was a "convenient species of medium in which [taxes] are to be paid." Washington would eventually sign the bill into law.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's push for a national bank was not an isolated event but a broader, long-running effort to establish a central banking system in the United States—one that would ultimately result in the Federal Reserve.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] While Hamilton's vision laid the groundwork for a structured financial system, the concept of centralized banking has remained one of the most polarizing economic debates in American history, garnering both staunch criticism and fervent support from economists and the public alike.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In 1791, Hamilton submitted the *Report on the Establishment of a Mint* to the House of Representatives.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Many of Hamilton's ideas for this report were from European economists, resolutions from the 1785 and 1786 Continental Congress meetings, and people such as Robert Morris, Gouverneur Morris and Thomas Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Because the most circulated coins in the United States at the time were Spanish currency, Hamilton proposed that minting a United States dollar weighing almost as much as the Spanish peso would be the simplest way to introduce a national currency.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton differed from European monetary policymakers in his desire to overprice gold relative to silver, on the grounds that the United States would always receive an influx of silver from the West Indies.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Despite his own preference for a monometallic gold standard, he ultimately issued a bimetallic currency at a fixed 15:1 ratio of silver to gold.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton proposed that the U.S. dollar should have fractional coins using decimals, rather than eighths like the Spanish coinage.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] This innovation was originally suggested by Superintendent of Finance Robert Morris, with whom Hamilton corresponded after examining one of Morris's Nova Constellatio coins in 1783.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He also desired the minting of small value coins, such as silver ten-cent and copper cent and half-cent pieces, for reducing the cost of living for the poor.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] One of his main objectives was for the general public to become accustomed to handling money on a frequent basis.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] By 1792, Hamilton's principles were adopted by Congress, resulting in the Coinage Act of 1792, and the creation of the mint.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] There was to be a ten-dollar gold Eagle coin, a silver dollar, and fractional money ranging from one-half to fifty cents.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The coining of silver and gold was issued by 1795.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Smuggling off American coasts was an issue before the Revolutionary War, and after the Revolution it was more problematic.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Along with smuggling, lack of shipping control, pirating, and a revenue imbalance were also major problems.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In response, Hamilton proposed to Congress to enact a naval police force called revenue cutters in order to patrol the waters and assist the custom collectors with confiscating contraband.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] This idea was also proposed to assist in tariff controlling, boosting the American economy, and promote the merchant marine.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] It is thought that his experience obtained during his apprenticeship with Nicholas Kruger was influential in his decision-making.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Concerning some of the details of the System of Cutters, Hamilton wanted the first ten cutters in different areas in the United States, from New England to Georgia.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Each of those cutters was to be armed with ten muskets and bayonets, twenty pistols, two chisels, one broad-ax and two lanterns.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The fabric of the sails was to be domestically manufactured; and provisions were made for the employees' food supply and etiquette when boarding ships.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Congress established the Revenue Cutter Service on August 4, 1790, which is viewed as the birth of the United States Coast Guard.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] One of the principal sources of revenue Hamilton prevailed upon Congress to approve was an excise tax on whiskey.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In his first Tariff Bill in January 1790, Hamilton proposed to raise the three million dollars needed to pay for government operating expenses and interest on domestic and foreign debts by means of an increase on duties on imported wines, distilled spirits, tea, coffee, and domestic spirits.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] It failed, with Congress complying with most recommendations excluding the excise tax on whiskey.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The same year, Madison modified Hamilton's tariff to involve only imported duties; it was passed in September.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In response of diversifying revenues, as three-fourths of revenue gathered was from commerce with Great Britain, Hamilton attempted once again during his *Report on Public Credit* when presenting it in 1790 to implement an excise tax on both imported and domestic spirits.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The taxation rate was graduated in proportion to the whiskey proof, and Hamilton intended to equalize the tax burden on imported spirits with imported and domestic liquor.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In lieu of the excise on production citizens could pay 60 cents by the gallon of dispensing capacity, along with an exemption on small stills used exclusively for domestic consumption.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He realized the loathing that the tax would receive in rural areas, but thought of the taxing of spirits more reasonable than land taxes.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Opposition initially came from Pennsylvania's House of Representatives protesting the tax.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] William Maclay had noted that not even the Pennsylvanian legislators had been able to enforce excise taxes in the western regions of the state.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton was aware of the potential difficulties and proposed inspectors the ability to search buildings that distillers were designated to store their spirits, and would be able to search suspected illegal storage facilities to confiscate contraband with a warrant.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Although the inspectors were not allowed to search houses and warehouses, they were to visit twice a day and file weekly reports in extensive detail.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton cautioned against expedited judicial means, and favored a jury trial with potential offenders.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] As soon as 1791, locals began to shun or threaten inspectors, as they felt the inspection methods were intrusive.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Inspectors were also tarred and feathered, blindfolded, and whipped.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton had attempted to appease the opposition with lowered tax rates, but it did not suffice.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Strong opposition to the whiskey tax by cottage producers in remote, rural regions erupted into the *Whiskey Rebellion* in 1794; in Western Pennsylvania and western Virginia, whiskey was the basic export product and was fundamental to the local economy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] This overwhelming display of force intimidated the leaders of the insurrection, ending the rebellion virtually without bloodshed.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's next report was his *Report on Manufactures*.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Although he was requested by Congress on January 15, 1790, for a report for manufacturing that would expand the United States' independence, the report was not submitted until December 5, 1791.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In the report, Hamilton quoted from *The Wealth of Nations* and used the French physiocrats as an example for rejecting agrarianism and the physiocratic theory, respectively.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton also refuted Smith's ideas of government noninterference, as it would have been detrimental for trade with other countries.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton also thought that the United States, being a primarily agrarian country, would be at a disadvantage in dealing with Europe.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In response to the agrarian detractors, Hamilton stated that the agriculturists' interest would be advanced by manufactures, and that agriculture was just as productive as manufacturing.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton argued for industrial policy to support a modern manufacturing industry in the United States.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He also encouraged immigration as a way to improve the American work force.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Congress shelved the report without much debate, except for Madison's objection to Hamilton's formulation of the general welfare clause, which Hamilton construed liberally as a legal basis for his extensive programs.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In 1791, Hamilton, along with Coxe and several entrepreneurs from New York City and Philadelphia formed the *Society for the Establishment of Useful Manufactures*, a private industrial corporation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In May 1792, the directors decided to examine the Great Falls of the Passaic River in New Jersey as a possible location for a manufacturing center.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] On July 4, 1792, the society directors met Philip Schuyler at Abraham Godwin's hotel on the Passaic River, where they led a tour prospecting the area for the national manufactory.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] It was originally suggested that they dig mile-long trenches and build the factories away from the falls, but Hamilton argued that it would be too costly and laborious.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The location at Great Falls of the Passaic River in New Jersey was selected due to access to raw materials, it being densely inhabited, and having access to water power from the falls of the Passaic.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The factory town was named *Paterson* after New Jersey's Governor William Paterson, who signed the charter.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The profits were to derive from specific corporates rather than the benefits to be conferred to the nation and the citizens, which was unlike the report.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton also suggested the first stock to be offered at $500,000 and to eventually increase to $1 million, and welcomed state and federal government subscriptions alike.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The company was never successful, with numerous shareholders reneged on stock payments and some going bankrupt.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] William Duer, the governor of the program, was sent to debtors' prison, where he died.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In spite of Hamilton's efforts to mend the disaster, the company folded.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] When France and Britain went to war in early 1793, all four members of the Cabinet were consulted on what to do.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] They and Washington unanimously agreed to remain neutral, and to have the French ambassador who was raising privateers and mercenaries on American soil, Edmond-Charles Genêt, recalled.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] However, in 1794, policy toward Britain became a major point of contention between the two parties.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton and the Federalists wished for more trade with Britain, the largest trading partner of the newly formed United States.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The Republicans saw monarchist Britain as the main threat to republicanism and proposed instead to start a trade war.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] To avoid war, Washington sent Chief Justice John Jay to negotiate with the British, with Hamilton largely writing Jay's instructions.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The result was a treaty denounced by the Republicans, but Hamilton mobilized support throughout the land.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The Jay Treaty passed the Senate in 1795 by exactly the required two-thirds majority.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The treaty resolved issues remaining from the Revolution, averted war, and made possible ten years of peaceful trade between the United States and Britain.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Historian George Herring notes the "remarkable and fortuitous economic and diplomatic gains" produced by the Treaty.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Several European states had formed the Second League of Armed Neutrality against incursions on their neutral rights; the cabinet was also consulted on whether the United States should join the alliance and decided not to.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] It kept that decision secret, but Hamilton revealed it in private to George Hammond, the British minister to the United States, without telling Jay or anyone else.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] His act remained unknown until Hammond's dispatches were read in the 1920s.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] This revelation may have had limited effect on the negotiations; Jay did threaten to join the League at one point, but the British had other reasons not to view the alliance as a serious threat.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's wife suffered a miscarriage while he was absent during his armed repression of the Whiskey Rebellion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In the wake of this, Hamilton tendered his resignation from office on December 1, 1794, giving Washington two months' notice, Before leaving his post on January 31, 1795, Hamilton submitted the *Report on a Plan for the Further Support of Public Credit* to Congress to curb the debt problem.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton grew dissatisfied with what he viewed as a lack of a comprehensive plan to fix the public debt.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He wished to have new taxes passed with older ones made permanent and stated that any surplus from the excise tax on liquor would be pledged to lower public debt.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] His proposals were included in a bill by Congress within slightly over a month after his departure as treasury secretary.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Some months later, Hamilton resumed his law practice in New York to remain closer to his family.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] After Jay resigned as Chief Justice in June 1795 to become Governor of New York, Attorney General William Bradford implored Hamilton to take the position, but Hamilton declined to focus on New York state politics.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's vision was challenged by Virginia agrarians Thomas Jefferson and James Madison, who formed the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] They favored strong state governments based in rural America and protected by state militias as opposed to a strong national government supported by a national army and navy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] They denounced Hamilton as insufficiently devoted to republicanism, too friendly toward corrupt Britain and the monarchy in general, and too oriented toward cities, industry and banking.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The two-party system began to emerge as political parties coalesced around competing interests.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] A congressional caucus, led by Madison, Jefferson, and William Branch Giles, began as an opposition group to Hamilton's financial programs.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton and his allies began to call themselves the Federalists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton assembled a nationwide coalition to garner support for the administration, including the expansive financial programs Hamilton had made administration policy and especially the president's policy of neutrality in the European war between Britain and France.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton publicly denounced French minister Genêt, who commissioned American privateers and recruited Americans for private militias to attack British ships and colonial possessions of British allies.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Eventually, even Jefferson joined Hamilton in seeking Genêt's recall.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] If Hamilton's administrative republic was to succeed, Americans had to see themselves first as citizens of a nation and experience an administration that proved firm and demonstrated the concepts found within the Constitution.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The Federalists did impose some internal direct taxes, but they departed from most implications of Hamilton's administrative republic as risky.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The Republicans opposed banks and cities and favored the series of unstable revolutionary governments in France.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] They built their own national coalition to oppose the Federalists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Both sides gained the support of local political factions, and each side developed its own partisan newspapers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Noah Webster, John Fenno, and William Cobbett were energetic editors for the Federalists, while Benjamin Franklin Bache and Philip Freneau were fiery Republican editors.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] All of their newspapers were characterized by intense personal attacks, major exaggerations, and invented claims.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In 1801, Hamilton established a daily newspaper, the *New York Evening Post*, and brought in William Coleman as its editor.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's and Jefferson's incompatibility was heightened by the unavowed wish of each to be Washington's principal and most trusted advisor.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] An additional partisan irritant to Hamilton was the 1791 United States Senate election in New York, which resulted in the election of Democratic-Republican candidate Aaron Burr over Federalist candidate Philip Schuyler, the incumbent and Hamilton's father-in-law.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton blamed Burr personally for this outcome, and negative characterizations of Burr began to appear in his correspondence thereafter.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The two men did work together from time to time thereafter on various projects, including Hamilton's army of 1798 and the Manhattan Water Company.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's resignation as secretary of the treasury in 1795 did not remove him from public life.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] With the resumption of his law practice, he remained close to Washington as an advisor and friend.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton influenced Washington in the composition of his farewell address by writing drafts for Washington to compare with the latter's draft, although when Washington contemplated retirement in 1792, he had consulted Madison for a draft that was used in a similar manner to Hamilton's.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In the election of 1796, under the Constitution as it stood then, each of the presidential electors had two votes, which they were to cast for different men from different states.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The one who received the most votes would become president, the second-most, vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] This system was not designed with the operation of parties in mind, as they had been thought disreputable and factious.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The Federalists planned to deal with this by having all their electors vote for John Adams, then vice president, and all but a few for Thomas Pinckney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Adams resented Hamilton's influence with Washington and considered him overambitious and scandalous in his private life; Hamilton compared Adams unfavorably with Washington and thought him too emotionally unstable to be president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton took the election as an opportunity: he urged all the northern electors to vote for Adams and Pinckney, lest Jefferson get in; but he cooperated with Edward Rutledge to have South Carolina's electors vote for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] If all this worked, Pinckney would have more votes than Adams, Pinckney would become president, and Adams would remain vice president, but it did not work.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The Federalists found out about it and northern Federalists voted for Adams but not for Pinckney, in sufficient numbers that Pinckney came in third and Jefferson became vice president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Adams resented the intrigue since he felt his service to the nation was much more extensive than Pinckney's.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In summer 1797, Hamilton became the first major American politician publicly involved in a sex scandal.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Six years earlier, in summer 1791, 34-year-old Hamilton became involved in an affair with 23-year-old Maria Reynolds.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] According to Hamilton, Maria approached him at his house in Philadelphia, claiming that her husband James Reynolds was abusive and had abandoned her, and she wished to return to her relatives in New York but lacked the means.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton recorded her address and subsequently delivered $30 personally to her boarding house, where she led him into her bedroom and "Some conversation ensued from which it was quickly apparent that other than pecuniary consolation would be acceptable".
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The two began an intermittent illicit affair that lasted approximately until June 1792.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] James Reynolds was aware of his wife's infidelity, and likely orchestrated it from the beginning.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He continually supported their relationship to extort blackmail money regularly from Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The common practice of the day for men of equal social standing was for the wronged husband to seek retribution in a duel.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] But Reynolds, of a lower social status and realizing how much Hamilton had to lose if his activity was made public, resorted to extortion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] After an initial request of $1,000, with which Hamilton complied, Reynolds invited Hamilton to renew his visits to his wife "as a friend" only to extort forced "loans" after each visit that, most likely in collusion, Maria solicited with her letters.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In the end, the blackmail payments totaled over $1,300 including the initial extortion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton at this point may have been aware of both spouses being involved in the blackmail, and he welcomed and strictly complied with James Reynolds' eventual request to end the affair.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In November 1792, James Reynolds and his associate Jacob Clingman were arrested for counterfeiting and speculating in Revolutionary War veterans' unpaid back wages.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Clingman was released on bail and relayed information to Democratic-Republican congressman James Monroe that Reynolds had evidence incriminating Hamilton in illicit activity as Treasury Secretary.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Monroe consulted with congressmen Muhlenberg and Venable on what actions to take and the congressmen confronted Hamilton on December 15, 1792.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton refuted the suspicions of financial speculation by exposing his affair with Maria and producing as evidence the letters by both of the Reynolds, proving that his payments to James Reynolds related to blackmail over his adultery, and not to treasury misconduct.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The trio agreed on their honor to keep the documents privately with the utmost confidence.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Five years later however, in the summer of 1797, the "notoriously scurrilous" journalist James T.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Callender published *A History of the United States for the Year 1796*.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The pamphlet contained accusations based on documents from the confrontation of December 15, 1792, taken out of context, that James Reynolds had been an agent of Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] On July 5, 1797, Hamilton wrote to Monroe, Muhlenberg, and Venable, asking them to confirm that there was nothing that would damage the perception of his integrity while Secretary of Treasury.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] All but Monroe complied with Hamilton's request.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] This led to Hamilton and Monroe engaging in an argument that almost culminated in a duel, before the conflict was averted by Aaron Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton then published a 100-page booklet, later usually referred to as the *Reynolds Pamphlet*, and discussed the affair in indelicate detail for the time.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's wife Elizabeth eventually forgave him, but never forgave Monroe.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Although Hamilton faced ridicule from the Democratic-Republican faction, he maintained his availability for public service.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] During the military build-up preceding the Quasi-War with France, and with the strong endorsement of Washington, Adams reluctantly appointed Hamilton a major general of the army.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton served as inspector general of the United States Army from July 18, 1798, to June 15, 1800.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Because Washington was unwilling to leave Mount Vernon unless it were to command an army in the field, Hamilton was the *de facto* head of the army, to Adams's considerable displeasure.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] If full-scale war broke out with France, Hamilton argued that the army should conquer the North American colonies of France's ally, Spain, bordering the United States.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton was prepared to march the army through the Southern United States if necessary.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] To fund the army, Hamilton wrote regularly to Oliver Wolcott Jr., his successor at the treasury, Representative William Loughton Smith, and U.S. senator Theodore Sedgwick.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] He urged them to pass a direct tax to fund the war.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Smith resigned in July 1797, as Hamilton complained to him for slowness, and urged Wolcott to tax houses instead of land.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The eventual program included taxes on land, houses, and slaves, calculated at different rates in different states and requiring assessment of houses, and a stamp act like that of the British before the Revolution, though this time Americans were taxing themselves through their own representatives.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] This provoked resistance in southeastern Pennsylvania nevertheless, led primarily by men such as John Fries who had marched with Washington against the Whiskey Rebellion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton aided in all areas of the army's development, and after Washington's death he was by default the senior officer of the United States Army from December 14, 1799, to June 15, 1800.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The army was to guard against invasion from France.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Adams, however, derailed all plans for war by opening negotiations with France that led to peace.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] There was no longer a direct threat for the army Hamilton was commanding to respond to.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Adams discovered that key members of his cabinet, namely Secretary of State Timothy Pickering and Secretary of War James McHenry, were more loyal to Hamilton than himself; Adams fired them in May 1800.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In November 1799, the Alien and Sedition Acts had left one Democratic-Republican newspaper functioning in New York City.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] When the last newspaper, the *New Daily Advertiser*, reprinted an article saying that Hamilton had attempted to purchase the *Philadelphia Aurora* to close it down, and said the purchase could have been funded by "British secret service money".
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton urged the New York Attorney General to prosecute the publisher for seditious libel, and the prosecution compelled the owner to close the paper.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In the 1800 presidential election, Hamilton worked to defeat both the Democratic-Republicans and also his party's own nominee, John Adams.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Jay, who had resigned from the Supreme Court to become Governor of New York, wrote on the back of a letter, "Proposing a measure for party purposes which it would not become me to adopt," and declined to reply.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Adams was running this time with Charles Cotesworth Pinckney, the elder brother of former vice presidential candidate Thomas.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton toured New England, again urging northern electors to hold firm for Pinckney in the renewed hope of making Pinckney president; and he again intrigued in South Carolina.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton's ideas involved coaxing middle-state Federalists to assert their non-support for Adams if there was no support for Pinckney and writing to more of the modest supports of Adams concerning his supposed misconduct while president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton expected to see southern states such as the Carolinas cast their votes for Pinckney and Jefferson, and would result in the former being ahead of both Adams and Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In accordance with these plans, and a recent personal rift with Adams, Hamilton wrote a pamphlet called *Letter from Alexander Hamilton, Concerning the Public Conduct and Character of John Adams, Esq.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] President of the United States* that was highly critical of him, though it closed with a tepid endorsement.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] But both he and Aaron Burr received 73 votes in the Electoral College.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] House of Representatives, under electoral laws of the time, had to choose between the two candidates.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Several Federalists who opposed Jefferson supported Burr, and for the first 35 ballots, Jefferson was denied a majority.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Before the 36th ballot, Hamilton threw his weight behind Jefferson, supporting the arrangement reached by James A.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Bayard of Delaware, in which five Federalist representatives from Maryland and Vermont abstained from voting, allowing those states' delegations to go for Jefferson, ending the impasse and electing Jefferson president rather than Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Even though Hamilton disliked Jefferson and disagreed with him on many issues, he viewed Jefferson as the lesser of two evils.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton spoke of Jefferson as being "by far not so a dangerous man" and of Burr as a "mischievous enemy" to the principal measure of the past administration.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] It was for that reason, along with the fact that Burr was a northerner and not a Virginian, that many Federalist representatives voted for him.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton wrote many letters to friends in Congress to convince the members to see otherwise.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In the end, Burr would become vice president after losing to Jefferson.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] However, according to several historians, the Federalists had rejected Hamilton's diatribe as reasons to not vote for Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] In his book *American Machiavelli: Alexander Hamilton and the Origins of US Foreign Policy*, historian John Lamberton Harper stated Hamilton could have "perhaps" contributed "to a degree" in Burr's defeat.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Ron Chernow, alternatively, claimed that Hamilton "squelched" Burr's chance at becoming president.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] When it became clear that Jefferson had developed his own concerns about Burr and would not support his return to the vice presidency, Burr sought the New York governorship in 1804 with Federalist support, against the Jeffersonian Morgan Lewis, but was defeated by forces including Hamilton.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Soon after Lewis' gubernatorial victory, the *Albany Register* published Charles D.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Cooper's letters, citing Hamilton's opposition to Burr and alleging that Hamilton had expressed "a still more despicable opinion" of the vice president at an Upstate New York dinner party.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Cooper claimed that the letter was intercepted after relaying the information, but stated he was "unusually cautious" in recollecting the information from the dinner.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Sensing an attack on his honor, and recovering from his defeat, Burr demanded an apology in the form of a letter.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton wrote a letter in response and ultimately refused because he could not recall the instance of insulting Burr.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton was also accused of recanting Cooper's letter out of cowardice.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] After a series of attempts to reconcile differences between the two failed, a duel was arranged through liaisons on June 27, 1804.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The concept of honor was fundamental to Hamilton's vision of himself and of the nation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] As evidence of the importance that honor held in Hamilton's value system, historians observe that Hamilton previously was a party to seven "affairs of honor" as a principal, and to three as an advisor or second.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Such affairs of honor were often concluded prior to reaching the final stage of a duel.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Before the duel, Hamilton wrote an explanation of his decision to participate while at the same time intending to "throw away" his shot.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] His desire to be available for future political matters also played a factor.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] A week before the duel, Hamilton and Burr both attended an annual Independence Day dinner held by the Society of the Cincinnati.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Separate accounts confirm that Hamilton was uncharacteristically effusive while Burr was, by contrast, uncharacteristically withdrawn.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Accounts also agree that Burr became roused when Hamilton, again uncharacteristically, sang a favorite song, which recent scholarship indicates was "How Stands the Glass Around", an anthem sung by military troops about fighting and dying in war.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The duel began at dawn on July 11, 1804, along the west bank of the Hudson River on a rocky ledge in Weehawken, New Jersey.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Both opponents were rowed over from Manhattan separately from different locations, since the location of the duel was not accessible from the west due to the steepness of the adjoining cliffs.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Coincidentally, the duel took place relatively close to the location of the duel that had ended the life of Hamilton's eldest son, Philip Hamilton, three years earlier.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Lots were cast for the choice of position and which second should start the duel.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Both were won by Hamilton's second, who chose the upper edge of the ledge for Hamilton facing the city and the rising sun to the east.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] After the seconds measured the paces, Hamilton, according to both William P.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Van Ness and Burr, raised his pistol "as if to try the light" and had to wear his glasses to prevent his vision from being obscured.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton also refused the more sensitive hairspring setting for the dueling pistols offered by Nathaniel Pendleton, and Burr was unaware of the option.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Burr shot Hamilton, delivering what proved to be a fatal wound, while Hamilton apparently "deloped", as he had indicated was his intention in his letter beforehand; and his shot went well above Burr's head, breaking a tree branch.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The seconds, Pendleton and Van Ness, disagreed on which man fired first in the duel.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Soon after, they measured and triangulated the shooting, but could not determine from which angle Hamilton had fired.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Biographer Ron Chernow contends that, after taking deliberate aim, Burr fired second.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Biographer James Earnest Cooke, however, believes that Burr took careful aim and shot first, and Hamilton fired while falling after being struck by Burr's bullet.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The shot hit Hamilton in the lower abdomen above his right hip.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The ball ricocheted off Hamilton's second or third false rib, fracturing it and causing considerable damage to his internal organs, particularly his liver and diaphragm, before becoming lodged in his first or second lumbar vertebra.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The paralyzed Hamilton was immediately attended by the same surgeon who tended to Hamilton's son Philip.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton was ferried to Greenwich Village and the boarding house of his friend William Bayard Jr., who was waiting on the dock.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] On his deathbed, Hamilton asked the Episcopal Bishop of New York, Benjamin Moore, to give him holy communion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Moore initially declined to do so on the grounds that participating in a duel was a mortal sin and that Hamilton, although undoubtedly sincere in his faith, was not a member of the Episcopalian denomination.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] After leaving, Moore was persuaded to return that afternoon by the urgent pleas of Hamilton's friends.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] After hearing Hamilton's solemn assurance that he repented his role in the duel, Moore gave him communion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] After final visits from his family, friends, and considerable suffering for at least 31 hours, Hamilton died at two o'clock the following afternoon, July 12, 1804, at Bayard's home just below present-day Gansevoort Street in Greenwich Village, New York City.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The city fathers halted all business at noon two days later for Hamilton's funeral.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] The procession route of about two miles organized by the Society of the Cincinnati had so many participants of every class of citizen that it took hours to complete and was widely reported nationwide by newspapers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Moore conducted Hamilton's funeral service at Trinity Church at present-day 89 Broadway in Manhattan.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Gouverneur Morris gave the eulogy and secretly established a fund to support his widow and children.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p02] Hamilton was buried in the church's cemetery.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] As a youth in the West Indies, Hamilton was an orthodox and conventional Presbyterian of the New Lights; he was mentored there by a former student of John Witherspoon, a moderate of the New School.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] He wrote two or three hymns, which were published in the local newspaper.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Robert Troup, his college roommate, noted that Hamilton was "in the habit of praying on his knees night and morning".
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] During the American Revolution, however, Hamilton became less religious and instead became "a conventional liberal with theistic inclinations who was an irregular churchgoer at best," according to Brown University historian Gordon S.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In his final years of life, though, Hamilton returned to his Protestant faith, and was Episcopalian.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] When the Constitutional Convention opened in Philadelphia in May 1787, stories circulated that Hamilton made two quips about God at the convention.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] During the French Revolution, Hamilton displayed a utilitarian approach to using religion for political ends, including maligning Thomas Jefferson as "the atheist", and insisting that Christianity and Jeffersonian democracy were incompatible.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] After 1801, Hamilton expressed his belief in Christianity, proposing a Christian Constitutional Society in 1802 to take hold of "some strong feeling of the mind" to elect "fit men" to office, and advocating "Christian welfare societies" for the poor.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] After being shot in his duel with Aaron Burr on July 11, 1804, Hamilton spoke of his belief in God's mercy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Moore initially declined to do so, on two grounds: that to participate in a duel was a mortal sin, and that Hamilton, although undoubtedly sincere in his faith, was not a member of the Episcopalian denomination.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] After leaving, Moore was persuaded to return that afternoon following urgent pleas of Hamilton's friends.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] After receiving Hamilton's solemn assurance that he never intended to shoot Burr and repented for his part in the duel, Moore gave him communion.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Bishop Moore returned the next morning, stayed with Hamilton for several hours until his death, and conducted his subsequent funeral service at Trinity Church.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton's birthplace had a large Jewish community, comprising roughly a quarter of Charlestown's white population by the 1720s.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] He came into contact with Jews on a regular basis; as a small boy, he was tutored by a Jewish schoolmistress, and had learned to recite the Ten Commandments in the original Hebrew.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Based primarily on the phonetic similarity of Lavien to a common Jewish surname, it has been suggested that Johann Lavien, the first husband of Hamilton's mother, was Jewish or of Jewish descent.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] On this contested foundation, it was rumored that Hamilton himself was born Jewish, a claim that gained some popularity early in the 20th century and which was given serious consideration in 2021 by Andrew Porwancher.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The belief that Lavien was Jewish was popularized by Gertrude Atherton in her 1902 novel *The Conqueror*, a fictionalized biography of Hamilton which made the earliest known written assertion that Hamilton was Jewish.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The consensus of mainstream scholars and historians, however, is that Hamilton was not Jewish.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton's interpretations of the Constitution, which are set forth in *The Federalist Papers*, remain highly influential, and continue to be cited in scholarly studies and court decisions.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Although the Constitution was ambiguous as to the exact balance of power between national and state governments, Hamilton consistently took the side of greater federal power at the expense of the states, which placed him at odds with Thomas Jefferson and other Founding Fathers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Jefferson, however, took a differing view.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Parsing text carefully, Jefferson argued that no specific authorization for the establishment of a national bank existed.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The controversy between the two was addressed in *McCulloch v.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Maryland*, which largely adopted Hamilton's view, granting the federal government broad freedom to select the best means to execute its constitutionally enumerated powers and confirmed the doctrine of implied powers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The American Civil War and the Progressive Era, Hamilton's defenders argue, demonstrated the sorts of crises and politics that Hamilton's administrative republic sought to avoid.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton's policies have proven greatly influential on the development of the U.S. government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] His constitutional interpretation, particularly of the Necessary and Proper Clause, set precedents for federal authority that are still cited by courts and are considered an authority on constitutional interpretation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Both John Adams and Jefferson, however, viewed Hamilton as unprincipled and dangerously aristocratic.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton's reputation was mostly negative in the Jeffersonian democracy and Jacksonian democracy eras.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] During the Jeffersonian era, Hamilton was criticized as a centralizer, sometimes to the point of accusing him of being a proponent of monarchy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Conversely, during the later Progressive Era, such figures as Herbert Croly, Henry Cabot Lodge, and Theodore Roosevelt praised Hamilton's leadership as a proponent of a strong national government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In the 19th and 20th centuries several Republicans wrote laudatory biographies on Hamilton prior to entering politics.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] According to Princeton University historian Sean Wilentz, Hamilton has been generally viewed favorably among contemporary scholars, who portray him as a visionary architect of a modern liberal capitalist economy and of a dynamic federal government headed by an energetic executive.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Conversely, these modern scholars favoring Hamilton portray Jefferson and his allies as relatively naïve and dreamy idealists.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton is not known to have ever owned slaves, although members of his family did.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] At the time of her death, Hamilton's mother owned two slaves and wrote a will leaving them to her sons.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Due to their illegitimacy, however, Hamilton and his brother were held ineligible to inherit her property and never took ownership of the slaves.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] As a youth in Saint Croix, Hamilton later worked for a company that traded slaves as well as sugar and other staples of the Transatlantic economy.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Historians have discussed with various levels of rigor whether Hamilton personally owned slaves later in life, with no definitive evidence ever surfacing.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton expressed support for limited emancipation during the American Revolutionary War, when he endorsed a plan to recruit slaves to serve in the Continental Army.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] As a necessary inducement, Hamilton wrote, the slave recruits should be promised their freedom upon enlistment.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] He dismissed objections that slaves were "too stupid" to fight well, arguing that their "want of cultivation" and "habit of subordination" made them ideal soldiers.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Whereas officers should be "men of sense and sentiment", good enlisted men were unthinking "machines", a role to which white men, unaccustomed to a "life of servitude", were comparatively less suited than slaves.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In 1785, he joined his close associate John Jay and more than 30 fellow New Yorkers in founding the New York Manumission Society.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The Society lobbied successfully for legislation to gradually abolish slavery in New York.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The 1799 act declared all children born after July 4, 1799 free pending a period of apprenticeship lasting 28 years for men and 25 years for women.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Slaves born prior to that date were not emancipated, and the final end of slavery in New York did not occur until 1827.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In the 1790s, Hamilton's political agenda sometimes came into conflict with proslavery interests.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] When the slave population of Saint-Domingue rose up against their French masters, Hamilton and other Federalists supported the revolutionaries and urged closer economic and diplomatic ties with new nation of Haiti.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] His suggestions shaped the Haitian constitution, promulgated the year after his death.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] At other times, political expediency led Hamilton to form close relationships with slaveholders like William Loughton Smith whose support was critical to the strength of the Federalist Party in South Carolina.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton has been portrayed as the patron saint of the American School economic philosophy that, according to historian Michael Lind, later dominated American economic policy after 1861.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton's ideas and work influenced 19th century German economist Friedrich List and Henry Charles Carey, who served as Abraham Lincoln's chief economic advisor during the Lincoln administration.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In fall 1781, Hamilton firmly supported government intervention in favor of business after the manner of Jean-Baptiste Colbert.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In contrast to the British policy of international mercantilism, which he believed skewed benefits to colonial and imperial powers, Hamilton was a pioneering advocate of protectionism.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] He is credited with the idea that industrialization was only possible with tariffs that protected the "infant industries" of an emerging nation.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Political theorists credit Hamilton with the creation of the modern administrative state, citing his arguments in favor of a strong executive, linked to the electoral support of the people, as the linchpin of an administrative republic.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The dominance of executive leadership in the formulation and carrying out of policy was, in Hamilton's view, essential to resist the deterioration of a republican government.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] As evidence of Hamilton's global influence, some scholars have compared Hamilton's recommendations to the development of Meiji Japan.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Hamilton has appeared as a significant figure in popular works of historical fiction, including many that focused on other American political figures of his time.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In comparison to other Founding Fathers, however, Hamilton attracted relatively little attention in American popular culture in the 20th century.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In 2015, he gained significant mainstream attention with the debut of the Broadway musical *Hamilton*, which is based on a biography by Ron Chernow.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] Lin-Manuel Miranda played Hamilton in the Original Broadway Cast.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] The musical was described by *The New Yorker* in February 2015 as "an achievement of historical and cultural reimagining.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In Miranda's telling, the headlong rise of one self-made immigrant becomes the story of America." The Off-Broadway production of *Hamilton* won the 2015 Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Musical and seven other Drama Desk Awards.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] In 2016, *Hamilton* received the Pulitzer Prize for Drama, and set a record for Tony Award nominations with 16, winning 11, including Best Musical.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] During the Obama administration, a plan to replace Hamilton on the ten-dollar bill was shelved due partly to the musical's popularity.
[src:alexander-hamilton/alexander-hamilton-p03] On July 3, 2020, Disney+ released the movie *Hamilton*, an authorized film of the Broadway stage production performed by the original cast.
